<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-04-11T17:29:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-04-11T17:29:00-05:00" n="159" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d159">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.24/60</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Russia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_FDR1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Francis</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Vologda</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-04-12T01:00:00+02:31"><hi rend="italic">April 12,
                                            1918, 1 a.m.</hi></date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received April 16, 10.22
                                    a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>89. Daily reports that Germans rapidly making purchases, and that
                                German purchasing commission will arrive within a few days. <pb facs="0168" n="118" xml:id="pg_118"/> Military attaché joins me
                                in recommending that purchase of such supplies be assigned to Consul
                                General at Moscow as civilian committee making little headway. Such
                                purchases should be made without delay and assembled at Archangel.
                                Consul General is familiar with matter and can engage competent men
                                therefor. I shall cooperate with him if you desire. See my Nos. 50
                                and 44.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed><persName corresp="#p_FDR1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Francis</hi></persName></signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>